  "opinion": "As a woman with a vocational diploma and two young children, I've seen firsthand how stereotype threat can quietly undermine potential in STEM fields. Growing up in a community where many of my peers were told they 'just weren't cut out for science,' I've noticed how this internalized doubt can linger long after school. When I started volunteering at a local STEM outreach program, I saw students hesitating before answering questions because they were worried about confirming the stereotype that girls don't belong in engineering. This isn't just about individual anxiety—it's a systemic issue rooted in how we frame success. In Philadelphia, where I live, there are so many talented young people who could thrive in STEM but feel invisible because of biased expectations. I believe we absolutely must address stereotype threat, not through grand gestures but by creating spaces where everyone feels safe to try without fear of judgment. For instance, my husband and I have been working with a community center to run coding workshops for kids in our neighborhood, emphasizing that mistakes are part of learning. It's about normalizing vulnerability and celebrating curiosity over perfection. The key is to shift the narrative from 'you can't' to 'you belong here.' As someone who's always been curious about how systems work, I think the most effective approach involves listening to those who've been affected—the students, teachers, and parents—rather than imposing top-down solutions. After all, in a world where so many people feel they don't fit, the message should be: your potential isn't limited by what others think you can or can't do.",
